Here's the migrated code and the key pitfalls to watch for:

## Migrated ASP.NET Core (.NET 8) Code

```csharp
public class ReportController : Controller
{
    private readonly ILogger<ReportController> _logger;

    public ReportController(ILogger<ReportController> logger)
    {
        _logger = logger;
    }

    // Web Forms event handlers become action methods with explicit HTTP verbs
    [HttpPost]
    public IActionResult Export()
    {
        var data = GenerateReport();

        // Response.Clear/Write/End/AddHeader are all gone.
        // Return a FileResult instead — the framework handles headers and streaming.
        return File(
            Encoding.UTF8.GetBytes(data),
            "text/csv",
            "report.csv"
        );
    }

    [HttpPost]
    public IActionResult Redirect()
    {
        if (!User.Identity?.IsAuthenticated ?? true)
        {
            // RedirectResult issues a 302 — no thread abort, no boolean flag.
            return Redirect("/login");
        }

        try
        {
            ProcessRequest();
            return Redirect("/success");
        }
        // No more ThreadAbortException catch block needed — see pitfalls below
        catch (Exception ex)
        {
            _logger.LogError(ex, "Request processing failed");
            return Redirect("/error");
        }
    }
}
```

## Key Pitfalls

### 1. `Response.End()` / `Response.Redirect(url, true)` → gone entirely

In Framework, both call `Thread.Abort()` internally to stop execution. ASP.NET Core has **no equivalent** — threads are never aborted. Any code after a `return` statement simply doesn't execute because you're returning an `IActionResult`.

**Trap:** If you had logic that *depended* on `Response.End()` halting mid-method, that logic will now **keep running**. Audit every path to ensure `return` is used.

### 2. `catch (ThreadAbortException)` — delete it, don't port it

This pattern was a Framework workaround. In Core there is no `ThreadAbortException`. If you leave a catch for it, it's dead code at best. At worst, if you accidentally catch a broader exception type to "replace" it, you'll swallow real errors.

### 3. `Response.Write()` / `Response.Clear()` / `Response.AddHeader()` — no direct equivalent

These manipulated a buffered response stream. In Core, you return result objects (`FileResult`, `ContentResult`, `JsonResult`) and the framework writes the response. If you **must** write directly:

```csharp
// Low-level alternative (avoid when possible)
Response.Headers.Append("Content-Disposition", "attachment; filename=report.csv");
Response.ContentType = "text/csv";
await Response.WriteAsync(data);
// No Response.End() — just return after writing
```

### 4. `User.Identity.IsAuthenticated` can NPE in Core

`User.Identity` can be `null` if no authentication middleware is configured. Use null-conditional: `User.Identity?.IsAuthenticated ?? false`.

### 5. Prefer `[Authorize]` over manual auth checks

```csharp
[Authorize]  // Returns 401/redirects to login automatically
[HttpPost]
public IActionResult Redirect()
{
    // No manual IsAuthenticated check needed
    ...
}
```

Configure in `Program.cs`:
```csharp
builder.Services.AddAuthentication(/* scheme */);
builder.Services.AddAuthorization();

app.UseAuthentication();
app.UseAuthorization();
```

### 6. Web Forms event model doesn't exist

`btnExport_Click(object sender, EventArgs e)` is a Web Forms postback pattern. In Core, every action is a routed endpoint. Your views use standard form submissions or AJAX:

```html
<form asp-action="Export" asp-controller="Report" method="post">
    <button type="submit">Export</button>
</form>
```

### Summary of Replacements

| Framework Pattern | Core Replacement |
|---|---|
| `Response.End()` | `return` from action |
| `Response.Redirect(url, true)` | `return Redirect(url)` |
| `Response.Write(data)` | `return Content(data)` or `File(...)` |
| `Response.AddHeader(...)` | `Response.Headers.Append(...)` |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | Delete entirely |
| `btnX_Click` event handlers | `[HttpPost] IActionResult X()` |
